Overview
This workflow guides order management teams through the process of:
1. 2. 3. 4. Identifying orders flagged with invalid ship-to addresses
Verifying the correct address using Google Maps
Updating the address in the Nexus system
Releasing the corrected order for fulfillment
Prerequisites
Access to the Nexus Order Management System
Access to Google Maps (maps.google.com)
Appropriate user permissions to edit and release orders in Nexus
Customer contact information (for cases where address cannot be verified
independently)
Workflow Steps
Step 1: Identify Invalid Address Orders
1. Log in to the Nexus Order Management System
2. Navigate to Orders > Exception Queue or Invalid Address Orders
3. Filter orders by status: Address Invalid or Ship-To Error
4. Note the Order ID, Customer Name, and flagged address
Step 2: Address Verification via Google Maps
1. Open Google Maps in your browser
2. Copy the flagged ship-to address from Nexus
3. Paste it into the Google Maps search bar
4. Verify the following:
Street number and name exist
City, State, and ZIP code match
The location is a valid deliverable address (not a vacant lot, body of water, etc.)
5. If the address is found with suggestions or corrections, note the corrected address
6. If the address cannot be found, contact the customer to confirm their correct address
Tip: Use Google Maps Street View to visually confirm the address is a real, deliverable
location.
Step 3: Correcting Address in Nexus
1. Return to Nexus and open the flagged order by Order ID
2. Click Edit Order or Modify Ship-To Address
3. Update the following fields as needed:
Field Example
Street Address Line 1 123 Main Street
Street Address Line 2 Apt 4B (if applicable)
City Chicago
State / Province IL
ZIP / Postal Code 60601
Country US
4. 5. Click Validate Address (if available) to confirm the corrected address passes system
validation
Add a note/comment to the order log:
Address corrected via Google Maps verification on [Date].
Original: [Old Address]
Corrected: [New Address]
Updated by: [Your Name]
6. Click Save Changes
Step 4: Releasing the Order
1. After saving the corrected address, navigate back to the order summary
2. Confirm the order status has changed from Address Invalid to Address Verified or
Ready to Ship
3. Click Release Order or Submit for Fulfillment
4. Confirm the release action in the pop-up dialog
5. Verify the order now appears in the Active Orders or Fulfillment Queue
Common Invalid Address Scenarios
Scenario Resolution
Missing ZIP code Look up correct ZIP on Google Maps or USPS
Misspelled street name Correct spelling using Google Maps suggestion
Wrong city/state combo Verify and update city and state to match ZIP
Missing apartment/suite number Contact customer to confirm unit number
PO Box not accepted Ask customer for physical street address
Address not found at all Contact customer directly to confirm address
Best Practices
Always log the original and corrected address in the order notes
Never guess an address — verify via Google Maps or contact the customer
Check carrier restrictions — some carriers don’t deliver to PO Boxes or certain zip
codes
Escalate orders where the customer cannot be reached within 24 hours
Document all corrections for audit and compliance purposes
FAQs
Q: What if Google Maps shows a different ZIP code than the customer provided?
Use the ZIP code confirmed by Google Maps, as it is likely more accurate. Note both in
the order comments.
Q: Can I release a partially verified address?
No. All address fields must be fully verified before releasing the order to prevent delivery
failures.
Q: What if the customer insists on an address Google Maps cannot verify?
Escalate to your supervisor and place the order on hold until the address can be
confirmed through alternative means (e.g., calling the customer).
Q: How long should an order stay in the invalid address queue?
Follow your company’s SLA — typically 24–48 hours before escalation.
Escalation Contact
If an address cannot be resolved within the standard timeframe, escalate to:
Team Lead / Supervisor — for unresolvable addresses
Customer Service — to contact the customer directly
Carrier Support — to check if the address is deliverable in their network